m in crisis, technical understanding. Weaknesses: communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nCandidate D: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Negatives: regarded as a know-it-all, has a hot temper, weak leadership, arrogant. So teamwork issues.\n\nWe need to decide provisional preference. Let's weigh criteria: reliability/responsibility: D takes responsibility seriously; B is conscientious; C is reliable? Not explicitly but quick decisions and calm. A anticipates danger.\n\nTechnical competence: A spatial vision, complex connections; B weather assessment, computer; C understands complicated tech; D problem solving, concentration.\n\nCalmness/pressure: B handles stress well; C keeps calm in crisis; D concentration; A unknown.\n\nDecision-making: C quick correct decisions; A anticipates dangerous; D responds adequately; B good weather assessment.\n\nTeamwork/communication: B nasty remarks, uncooperative; C difficulty communicating, egocentric; D arrogant, weak leadership; A show-off, not open to new ideas.\n\nProfessional development: B excellent computer skills, but weak memory for numbers; C not willing to further education; D know-it-all; A not open to new ideas.\n\nOverall, B seems strong on stress handling and weather, crucial for long flights, but teamwork issues could be serious. C has good decision speed and calmness, but communication issues and lack of development. D strong problem solving and responsibility, but leadership and temperament issues. A strong anticipation and leadership but not open to new ideas and show-off.\n\nWhich is best? Long-distance flights require crew coordination, calm under stress, decision-making, technical competence, reliability. Teamwork is critical. B's uncooperativeness could be a safety risk. C's communication difficulty also risk. D's arrogance and weak leadership also risk. A's show-off and closed